        <section class="content-section">
            <h2>Modern Mathematics</h2>
            <p>The term modern mathematics, in the title, is supposed to mean mathematics that we study today, which is an inside-out view of the subject. Often while doing regular-day mathematics we consider mathematical things (something, some specified data maybe with some structure or symmetry or any other property for that matter). Then we consider studying the data inside each such thing, one by one, and then looking at how that data can be transferred between them via something called mappings.</p>
            
            <p>While in the modern view of mathematics we are privileged to have a philosophy of an outside-in view. Where we do not specify what data is there inside such a thing, but instead specify mappings coming in and going out of that thing. This is similar to a social belief that <em>"more than what we have (in this case the data inside) what characterizes us better is what we do for the society (the mappings in this case)"</em>.</p>
            
